'''Taha Abdi Ali''' (born 1 July 1998) is a Swedish professional [[Football player|footballer]] who plays as a left [[winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Swedish]] club [[Malmö FF]] and the [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden national team]].

He has previously played for [[Sundbybergs IK]], [[:sv:IFK Stocksund|IFK Stocksund]], [[Sollentuna FK]], [[Örebro SK]], [[Helsingborgs IF]], [[Västerås SK Fotboll|Västerås SK]].

== Club career ==
Ali grew up in [[Tensta]] and started playing football at the age of eight in [[Spånga IS]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jag känner mig redo för allsvenskan |website= Nyhetsbyrån Järva |date=21 February 2021 |url=https://www.nyhetsbyranjarva.se/jag-kanner-mig-redo-for-allsvenskan/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> At the end of 2013, he joined Sundbybergs IK at the age of 15.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Taha Ali till Allsvenskan! |url=https://www.sikfotboll.se/nyheter/2021/2/8/tidigare-sundbybergsspelaren-taha-ali-klar-for-allsvenskan/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website= Sundbybergs IK Fotboll}}</ref> Ali scored three goals in 11 games for the club in [[Division 2 (Swedish football)|Division 2]] in 2017. He then played two years in [[IFK Stocksund]]. For the 2020 season, Ali was signed by [[Sollentuna FK]]. He scored 10 goals and as many assists in 29 games in the 2020 [[Ettan Fotboll|Ettan]] Norra, where Sollentuna finished in third place.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 February 2021 |title=Succédebut för ÖSK:s nya värvning från Sollentuna FK |url=https://www.mitti.se/sport/succedebut-for-osks-nya-varvning-fran-sollentuna-fk/repubj!r14EAnFSb5Q7m5HF5ZSz5A/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=mitti.se |language=sv}}</ref>

In February 2021, Ali was signed by [[Örebro SK]], where he signed a three-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Taha Ali skriver på för ÖSK Fotboll |url=https://oskfotboll.se/osk/aktuellt/nyheter-2021/2021-02-06-taha-ali-skriver-pa-for-osk-fotboll.html |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=ÖSK Fotboll |language=sv}}</ref> Ali made his [[Allsvenskan]] debut on 24 May 2021 in a 2–1 loss to Malmö FF, where he was substituted in the 84th minute.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Örebro vs. Malmö – 24 May 2021 – Soccerway |url=https://nr.soccerway.com/matches/2021/05/24/sweden/allsvenskan/orebro-sportklubb-fotboll/malmo-fotbollsforening/3445171/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> After scant playing time (three competitive games in total), Ali was loaned out to [[Superettan]] club [[Västerås SK Fotboll|Västerås SK]] in August 2021 on a loan deal for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Klart: Taha Ali ansluter på lån från Örebro SK |url=https://www.vskfotboll.nu/klart-taha-ali-ansluter-pa-lan-fran-orebro-sk/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=vskfotboll.nu |date=12 August 2021 |language=sv-SE}}</ref> The loan was a success for Ali, who scored two goals and eight assists in 15 games, helping Västerås stay in Superettan.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ali om superettan-succén och framtiden: "Självklart skulle man någon dag vilja spela för AIK" |url=https://www.fotbollskanalen.se/superettan/ali-om-superettan-succen-och-framtiden-sjalvklart-skulle-man-nagon-dag-vilja-s/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=Fotbollskanalen |language=sv}}</ref> He was also awarded the VLT prize as Västerås' best athlete in 2021, becoming the first footballer from Västerås SK to win the award.

In February 2022, Ali was signed by [[Helsingborgs IF|Helsingborg]], where he signed a four-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kuduzovic |first=Midhat |date=7 February 2022 |title=Taha Ali klar för HIF |url=https://www.hif.se/taha-ali-klar-hif/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=HIF |language=sv-SE}}</ref> In January 2023, he joined fellow Swedish club [[Malmö FF]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hd.se/2023-01-09/klart-taha-ali-lamnar-hif-for-malmo-ff |title=Klart: Taha Ali lämnar HIF för Malmö FF |website=Helsingborgs Dagblad |language=sv |date=9 January 2023 }}</ref> where he won his first league title in November later that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/article/malmo-swedish-league-champion-elfsborg-f32d67d70ccc120b61f76835cc8f2437 |title=Malmo wins Swedish league by beating and overtaking Elfsborg in final round |publisher=AP News |date=12 November 2023 }}</ref>

== International career ==
Ali made his senior debut for [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] in a friendly match against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 12 January 2024.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Sweden 2–1 Estonia |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/690688/estonia-sweden |date=12 January 2024 |publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 12 May 2026, Ali was named in the Sweden squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-05-12 |title=Mystiskt inlägg efter petningen |url=https://www.expressen.se/sport/fotboll/landslaget/har-ar-sveriges-trupp-till-fotbolls-vm-2026/ |access-date=2026-05-15 |website=www.expressen.se |language=sv}}</ref>

==Futsal career==
Ali played six international matches and scored one goal between 2018 and 2019 for the [[Sweden men's national futsal team|Swedish national futsal team]]. At club level, he played for Nacka Juniors FF and [[Hammarby IF Futsal|Hammarby Futsal]] in the [[Swedish Futsal League]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Taha Abdi Ali – Spelarstatistik – Svensk fotboll |url=https://www.svenskfotboll.se./spelarfakta/taha-abdi-ali/3e9983d5-da36-436b-8d34-27eb1d90fcb9/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=svenskfotboll.se |language=sv |archive-date=30 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220630093256/https://www.svenskfotboll.se/spelarfakta/taha-abdi-ali/3e9983d5-da36-436b-8d34-27eb1d90fcb9/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Ali was born in Stockholm, Sweden in 1998 to Somali parents. His parents arrived in Sweden as refugees due to the [[Somali Civil War]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0294-1c89095be696-121f8306c089-1000--human-rights-day-how-football-helped-defy-the-odds/ |title=Human Rights Day: How football helped defy the odds |publisher=UEFA |date=10 December 2024 |access-date=1 June 2026}}</ref>

On 11th May 2026, he was called up to the 26-man [[Sweden men's national football team]] for the 2026 World Cup by manager [[Graham Potter]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/sweden-squad-announcement-world-cup-graham-potter |title=Sweden squad announcement: World Cup – Graham Potter |publisher=FIFA |date=12 May 2026 |access-date=1 June 2026}}</ref>

